The stow --adopt command is a lifesaver when you already have configuration files (dotfiles) in your home directory and you want to move them into a central Git-managed folder without manually cutting and pasting everything.

By default, stow tries to create symlinks. If a file already exists where the link should go, it throws an error. Using --adopt tells Stow: "Take the existing file, move its contents into my stow directory, and then link it back."

The Workflow
Here is the standard 3-step process to bring an existing config into your dotfiles folder:

Prepare your folder: Ensure your dotfiles directory structure matches your target. For example, if your config is at ~/.config/nvim/init.lua, your stow folder should look like ~/dotfiles/nvim/.config/nvim/init.lua.

Run the command: Navigate to your dotfiles folder and run:
stow -A nvim (or stow --adopt nvim)

Reset the changes: Stow will "adopt" the files, but it often marks them as changed in Git because it technically modified them during the move. You’ll want to check git diff and then git reset --hard to ensure your local files match your repository state.

Key Flags to Know
Flag	Meaning
-A / --adopt	Imports existing files into the stow package.
-n / --simulate	Highly recommended. Shows what would happen without doing it.
-v	Verbose mode; tells you exactly which files are being moved.
-t ~	Target directory (usually your home directory).
A Quick Warning
Be careful! Using --adopt overwrites the files inside your stow directory with the versions currently living in your home folder. If you have a clean config in your Git repo and a messy one in your home folder, --adopt will overwrite your clean Git version.

Always run a dry run first:
stow --adopt -n -v nvim

